<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Xenocrates</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Fri Jul 25, 2003; substantive revision Wed Sep 3, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
As Diogenes Laertius reports (D.L., IV 14 = T 2 IP), Xenocrates (of
Chalcedon, a city on the Asian side of the Bosporus opposite
Byzantium) became head of the Academy after the death of Speusippus,
in 339/338 (&ldquo;in the second year of the 110th Olympiad&rdquo;).
D.L. adds that he held that position for twenty-five years and died at
82. Accordingly, his life dates are generally given as
396/395&ndash;314/313 BCE.</p>

<p>
On the death of Plato, when Speusippus became head of the Academy,
Xenocrates and Aristotle may have left Athens together at the
invitation of Hermeias of Atarneus (Strabo, <em>Geography</em>, XIII
57), and Xenocrates returned to succeed Speusippus. According to D.L.
(IV 3 = T 21 IP), this was at Speusippus&rsquo; request, while the
<em>Academicorum Index Herculanensis</em> (cols. 6,41&ndash;7,18:
Fleisher 2018, 175&ndash;176 = T 1 IP) tells us that the younger
members of the Academy voted &mdash;for the first time&mdash;and
confirmed Xenocrates (over Heraclides of Pontus and Menedemus of
Pyrrha) by a narrow margin as the first elected head of the school.
These two accounts, although not incompatible, offer two different
versions of the succession, and it does not appear possible to get
behind them to what really happened.</p>

<p>
D.L.&rsquo;s bibliography (IV 11&ndash;14 = T 2 IP) lists over seventy
titles attributed to Xenocrates, none of which survives, not even in
the form of clearly identifiable quotations in other authors. As with
Speusippus, the reconstruction of Xenocrates&rsquo; doctrines depends
heavily on Aristotle who, frustratingly, often refrains from naming
Xenocrates explicitly. Although Aristotle never directly names
Xenocrates when discussing his philosophical views, possible
references to his doctrines are signalled through certain recurring
formulas; for instance, when Aristotle speaks of &ldquo;those who
posited the Forms&rdquo; (a phrase that often includes Plato and
Xenocrates), of &ldquo;those who posited one nature for mathematical
objects and Forms,&rdquo; or of &ldquo;those who defined the soul as
&lsquo;self-moving number&rsquo;&rdquo; (more on this below).</p>

<p>
Throughout this entry, citations of Xenocrates&rsquo; fragments follow
the numbering in Isnardi Parente&rsquo;s revised edition (2012),
hereafter &lsquo;IP&rsquo;.</p>

<p>
Sextus Empiricus tells us (<em>Adv. math.</em> I &sect;16 = fr. 1 IP)
that Xenocrates made explicit the tripartite division of philosophy
that was implicit in Plato into &lsquo;physics&rsquo;,
&lsquo;ethics&rsquo;, and &lsquo;logic&rsquo;. This schema later
became canonical in Stoicism and Hellenistic philosophy more
generally. As is standard with this terminology, what we today refer
to as metaphysics and theory of knowledge are subsumed under
&lsquo;physics&rsquo; and &lsquo;logic&rsquo;, respectively.
Sextus&rsquo; report about the standard division of philosophy
transmitted by Xenocrates but ultimately derived from Plato is typical
of much of what we hear about him: Xenocrates appears to have been at
least as concerned to carry on Plato&rsquo;s thought as to promote
ideas of his own.</p>

<p>
Xenocrates&rsquo; system has sometimes been read as anticipating ideas
that would become prominent in the Middle Platonic tradition (e.g.,
Dillon 2003. For an overview of major scholarly approaches to the
material preserved on the Early Academy, see the entry on
 <a href="../speusippus/">Speusippus</a>).
 In this entry, significant focus is placed on Aristotle&rsquo;s
texts, complemented by material preserved by other authors, with less
emphasis on potential continuity with later traditions. What survives
of Xenocrates&rsquo; views is here divided into four sections:
Metaphysics, Xenocrates and the <em>Timaeus</em>, Theory of Knowledge,
and Ethics. The available material is considerably more abundant for
metaphysics, while our sources for epistemology and ethics are far
more limited.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
